    public override async Task SeedAsync()
    {
        // ── Overview (Article) ───────────────────────────────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "OEE Overview",
            Slug = "oee-overview",
            Summary = "What Overall Equipment Effectiveness is, the three factors (Availability x Performance x Quality), world-class benchmarks, the Six Big Losses, and how to read the OEE dashboard.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Article,
            EstimatedMinutes = 6,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 1,
            AppRoutes = """["/oee"]""",
            Tags = """["oee","manufacturing","metrics"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## OEE Overview\n\nOEE (**Overall Equipment Effectiveness**) is the single most widely used measure of how well a machine or work center runs. It answers three questions in one number: *Is the machine running when it should be? Is it running as fast as it should? Is it making good parts?* You see the score per work center over the dates you're looking at, plus where the losses are hiding — so you know what to fix first.\n\n### The OEE Formula\n\nOEE is three factors multiplied together, each a percentage:\n\n**OEE = Availability x Performance x Quality**\n\nBecause you multiply them, OEE always lands below your weakest factor. A machine that is 90% available, running at 90% of speed, and 90% good is only 0.9 x 0.9 x 0.9 = 72.9% effective. The losses compound — they don't average out. That's the whole point of OEE: three numbers that each look fine can still add up to a mediocre machine.\n\n### Factor 1 — Availability\n\nAvailability asks: *did the machine run when it was supposed to?* It's run time divided by the time you planned for it to run. You start with the minutes it was scheduled, take out planned stops (breaks, scheduled maintenance) to get available time, then compare the minutes it actually ran. Breakdowns, unplanned stops, and long changeovers all cost you Availability.\n\n### Factor 2 — Performance\n\nPerformance asks: *while it was running, did it run at full speed?* You compare the fastest possible time to make a part — the ideal cycle time — against how fast it actually ran. Short stops, idling, and running slow all drag Performance down. Performance should never top 100%. If it does, the ideal cycle time was set too fast to be real — that's a data problem to fix, not a machine beating physics.\n\n### Factor 3 — Quality\n\nQuality asks: *how many parts came out right the first time?* It's good parts divided by all parts made. Scrap and rework both pull it down — a part you had to rework wasn't made right the first time, so it counts against you.\n\n### World-Class OEE\n\nA work center earns a **world-class** star when it hits the recognized benchmark — about 85% OEE, which works out to roughly 90% Availability, 95% Performance, and 99% Quality. Most shops start well below that. Around 60% is normal for an operation that has never measured before. The good news: because the factors multiply, small gains compound quickly, so early improvements pay off fast.\n\n### The Six Big Losses\n\nEvery point of OEE you lose falls into one of six classic loss categories, grouped by the factor it hurts. Knowing which category is biggest tells you exactly where to aim your improvement effort.\n\n**Availability losses (uptime)**\n- **Equipment Failure** — breakdowns and unplanned stops.\n- **Setup & Adjustment** — changeover time, tooling changes, warm-up.\n\n**Performance losses (speed)**\n- **Idling & Minor Stops** — short stoppages, jams, blocked or starved conditions.\n- **Reduced Speed** — running slower than the ideal cycle time.\n\n**Quality losses (good parts)**\n- **Process Defects** — scrap and defects made while the machine runs steadily.\n- **Reduced Yield** — defects made during startup, warm-up, or right after a changeover.\n\nAdd up the minutes in all six and you get your total lost minutes. The tallest bar is where the money is.\n\n### Reading the Numbers\n\nEach work center shows its OEE score, the three factors, and part counts (total made, good, scrapped). A star marks the world-class centers. Above the centers you'll see the average OEE across your whole shop and how many centers hit world-class — a fast read on the operation as a whole. Pick a center to look closer: you'll see its score trended over time and its Six Big Losses spelled out, so you can tell whether a change actually helped and which loss is costing you most.\n\n### Where the Numbers Come From\n\nYou never type an OEE score — it's read straight from the work you already report. Run time and downtime come from clock and machine events. Good, scrap, and rework counts come from the quality and production records your team files as jobs run. OEE just gathers all of that and does the math. So the way to move the number is to fix the floor: cut a breakdown, speed up a changeover, chase down scrap. The score follows.\n\n### When to Use OEE\n\n- To find your worst-performing work center and the one factor dragging it down\n- To decide whether to invest in uptime (Availability), speed (Performance), or scrap reduction (Quality)\n- To check whether an improvement actually moved the number\n- To benchmark yourself against the world-class 85% target\n- To turn a vague 'the machine is slow' complaint into a specific, fixable loss","sections":[]}"""
        });

        // ── Walkthrough ──────────────────────────────────────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "OEE — Guided Tour",
